 is a sharp generational break between these groups. Finally, Carney demonstrates that tragic experience is often denied by the social discourse of Englishness, and that these playwrights make a crucial critical intervention by dramatizing the tragic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramay21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics in literature. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh1 aBarker, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurchill, Caryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHare, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266350340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442663503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442663503.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK